# Main/Apply.elm — EARLY

The Model-level state-transition layer. `applyAction` is the
single entry point for applying a validated action to the
Model — same function whether the input came from a local
gesture, a replay tick, or a wire broadcast.

## Status

- **Label:** EARLY. Extracted 2026-04-19 from the pre-split
  `Main.elm` monolith. DRY'd 2026-04-21 against
  `Game.Reducer` after the two applyAction functions were
  found to duplicate most of the board+hand transition logic.
- **Shape:** Pure. No Msg, no I/O, no rendering, no
  subscriptions.

## Name audit (2026-04-21)

Previously named `applyWireAction`; the "Wire" prefix was
leaking a serialization concern. The function doesn't care
where the action came from; it just applies it. Renamed to
`applyAction` so the Model-level applier and the pure
`Reducer.applyAction` now share a shape (both dispatch on
`WireAction`, both disambiguated by their module qualifier).

## Design: Reducer owns physics, Apply owns Model plumbing

`Game.Reducer.applyAction` is the authoritative
(board, hand) reducer. It handles the five physics actions
(Split, MergeStack, MergeHand, PlaceHand, MoveStack),
including the synthetic-HandCard fallback for replay of an
untracked seat's hand.

`Main.Apply.applyAction` delegates each physics action to
Reducer, then wraps the result with Model-level UI fields:

- `score = Score.forStacks post.board` — the running total.
- `setActiveHand post.hand ...` — writes the (possibly
  updated) active-player hand back into the `hands : List Hand`
  structure.
- `cardsPlayedThisTurn += 1` for MergeHand / PlaceHand only.
- A per-action `StatusMessage` (see "Status messages are an
  output" below).

The two actions Reducer can't handle live here inline:

- `CompleteTurn` — delegates to `Game.applyCompleteTurn`
  (classify, bank, deal, flip, age), then produces the
  turn-start celebrate message.
- `Undo` — no-op. V1 has no Undo button; action won't appear
  in logs we write.

## Status messages are an output (2026-04-22)

`applyAction` returns `ActionOutcome = { model, status }`, not
just a Model. The per-action message is generated at the point
of mutation — the branch that performs the MergeHand physics
also builds its `StatusMessage`, reading from the freshly-
computed post-board. No separate classifier diffing pre/post to
guess what happened.

Messages lifted verbatim from
`angry-cat/src/lyn_rummy/game/game.ts:2044-2076` so the feel
matches the TS original:

| Action | Condition | Text | Kind |
|---|---|---|---|
| Split | — | "Be careful with splitting!…" | Scold |
| PlaceHand | — | "On the board!" | Inform |
| MoveStack | — | "Moved!" | Inform |
| MergeStack / MergeHand | final size ≥ 3, clean board | "Combined! Clean board!" | Celebrate |
| MergeStack / MergeHand | final size ≥ 3, not clean | "Combined!" | Celebrate |
| MergeStack / MergeHand | final size < 3 | "Nice, but where's the third card?" | Scold |
| CompleteTurn | — | "Turn N — Player M to play." | Celebrate |
| Undo | — | "Undone." | Inform |

Clean-board detection uses `Game.StackType.getStackType` —
every stack must classify as Set / PureRun / RedBlackRun.

Callers pick how to consume the outcome:

- `Apply.commit : ActionOutcome -> Model` writes the outcome's
  status into the Model. Standard path for human actions.
- Callers that want to override the status (Main.elm's online
  CompleteTurn uses `statusForCompleteTurn` instead) read
  `outcome.model` directly and set their own status.
- Replay callers read `outcome.model` and ignore
  `outcome.status` — they keep their own lifecycle messages
  ("Replaying…", "Replay complete.").

## Public API

- `applyAction : WireAction -> Model -> ActionOutcome` — the
  dispatcher. Exhaustive over the 7 WireAction variants so the
  compiler catches drift if a new variant is added.
- `commit : ActionOutcome -> Model` — collapse an outcome into
  a Model by writing the outcome's status.
- `refereeBounds : BoardGeometry.BoardBounds` — the 800×600
  with 5px margin constant. Shared between
  `Main.ClickCompleteTurn` (referee pre-check) and any future
  client-side geometry validation. Matches the server's
  constant at `views/lynrummy_elm.go`.

Internal helpers:

- `applyPhysics` — threads (board, hand) through Reducer,
  rebuilds the Model with Score + active-hand updates.
  Idempotent on Reducer no-ops (bad target stack etc.): same
  board, same hand, same score.
- `applyCompleteTurn` — Game delegation + status text.
- `mergeStatus` / `splitStatus` / `placeHandStatus` /
  `moveStackStatus` / `undoStatus` — the per-action message
  builders. Colocated so each branch of applyAction produces
  its message right next to the mutation that earned it.
- `isCleanBoard` — every stack classifies as a valid group.

No other helpers — `applyChange`, `findHandCard`, the merge
glue, and the synthetic-HandCard fallback all live in Reducer
now, where they're closer to the transition they serve.

## Invariants preserved by applyAction

- `score` stays `Score.forStacks board` after any board
  change.
- `hands[activePlayerIndex]` shrinks by exactly one card on
  successful MergeHand / PlaceHand.
- `cardsPlayedThisTurn` increments by 1 on MergeHand /
  PlaceHand (regardless of whether Reducer no-ops — matches
  pre-DRY behavior; see "Pre-DRY quirk" below).
- `CompleteTurn` resets `cardsPlayedThisTurn = 0`, flips
  `activePlayerIndex`, advances `turnIndex`, via delegation to
  `Game.applyCompleteTurn`. GameState-layer invariants are
  Game's responsibility, not this module's.

### Pre-DRY quirk (preserved)

On a MergeHand whose target stack doesn't exist (or whose
tryHandMerge returns Nothing), the board + hand stay the same
but `cardsPlayedThisTurn` still increments. This matches the
pre-DRY behavior exactly — `applyHandOntoStack` returned
`model` unchanged but the pipeline `|> Game.noteCardsPlayed 1`
ran afterward. Not a bug worth fixing today; flagged here for
awareness.

## Dependencies

- `Game.BoardGeometry` — BoardBounds type for
  `refereeBounds`.
- `Game.Card`, `Game.CardStack` — domain types.
- `Game.Game` — `noteCardsPlayed`, `applyCompleteTurn`.
- `Game.Reducer` — `applyAction` for the physics half.
- `Game.Score` — `forStacks`.
- `Game.StackType` — `getStackType` for clean-board detection.
- `Game.WireAction` — `WireAction(..)` for the dispatch.
- `Main.State` — Model, ActionOutcome, StatusKind,
  StatusMessage, activeHand, setActiveHand.

## Tests

Currently no dedicated `Main/ApplyTest.elm`. Coverage is
indirect:

- `Game.ReducerTest` covers the physics half directly via
  `Reducer.applyAction`.
- `Game.GameTest` covers `Game.applyCompleteTurn`.
- `Game.DslConformanceTest` exercises end-to-end trick
  plays.
- `auto_player.py` provides end-to-end smoke coverage.

A dedicated test module could assert the Model-level wrappers
(Score recompute, setActiveHand, noteCardsPlayed increment,
CompleteTurn status text) but isn't written yet.
